Hi,

I have a question regarding the stability of silanized glass surfaces.
I am using a silanizing agent 3-acryloxypropyl)trichlorosilane for
treating the surface of glass by vapor phase chemistry.

I use this silanizing agent to treat the glass surface with acrylic
groups so that when I spin coat and UV polymerize another acrylate
polymer coating on the glass surface, it would stick to the glass
surface after polymerization.

However, for my experiments, I need to treat the surface with methanol
for a couple of days. I observe that the polymer film of acrylate
detaches from the glass surface inspite of silanizing the glass
surface with acrylic groups. I was hoping it would stick to the glass
via the acryloxypropyl siloxane bond.

I wanted to ask if you had any information on whether the methanol is
known to attack the siloxane bond with the glass? if yes, then do you
know of a better way to treat the glass surface so that the acrylate
coating would stay on it even after the methanol treatment? The
methanol treatment is necessary for my experiments and I cannot use
any other solvent instead of methanol, so the only way I have is to
make the adhesion stronger.

Please let me know if you have any suggestions on using an alternative
silane coupling agent or changing the coupling chemistry. Any other
ideas are also more than welcome.

Thanks in advance,
Prak
