Methanol won't attack the siloxane bond (they're only attacked by
base).  However, I'm not sure why you selected 3-
(acryloxypropyl)trichlorosilane as a coupling agent other than its
similarity to acrylate.  Since acrylates have COO- groups, I'd try a
positively charged silane, like 3-aminopropyltriethoxysilane.  There
are abundant procedures online for silanizing glass with APTES, since
this is a common procedure for treating microscope slides.  Back when
I used to use APTES, I got good results using toluene as the
silanizing solvent (different than procedures you'll find elsewhere).
Make up a 1% solution and dip the glass for 2-3 hours.  Make sure your
glass is extra clean, although if you're a coatings guy surely you
realize this...
