Doubt it...but you'd just have to try.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Next question I have is: Does it also mean that the trichlorosilane
&gt; chemistry for silanization is less effective than the triethoxysilane
&gt; or trimethoxysilane chemistry?
">

No, doesn't mean that at all.  In fact, trichlorosilanes are much more
reactive with -OH groups on the glass, but they're also sensitive to
atmospheric water (not so much an issue for the smaller chain, polar
trichlorosilanes).  Trialkoxysilanes are less reactive but easier to
handle.  Your problem seems to be that you're just choosing the wrong
functional group on your silane.  Also, -OH groups on glass are rather
sparse so the issue of trichlorosilane vs. trialkoxysilane is probably
moot anyway.  Furthermore, if you had an amino group on a
trichlorosilane, it'd spontaneously cyclize and thus 3-
aminopropyltrichlorosilane doesn't actually exist.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Also, I noticed that ethanol as a solvent does not remove the UV
&gt; polymerized acrylate film from glass surface while methanol does! This
&gt; does not make any sense to me.
">

Methanol is usually a better solvent than ethanol.  It doesn't really
surprise me.  I don't know how thick your acrylate film is, but
methanol may be better able to permeate into the acrylate than
ethanol.
